Continuous Glucose Monitoring (CGM) Systems - These systems, such as the Dexcom G5 Mobile CGM System, track glucose levels continuously throughout the day, providing real-time data and alerts for high or low readings.
Dexcom G5 Mobile CGM System - This continuous glucose monitoring system provides real-time glucose readings directly to a user's smartphone or smartwatch.
Continuous Glucose Monitors (CGMs) - These devices provide real-time glucose readings, eliminating the need for fingerstick testing.
Continuous Glucose Monitors (CGMs) - These devices provide real-time glucose readings throughout the day, eliminating the need for fingerstick testing.
Continuous Glucose Monitors (CGMs) - These devices provide real-time data on blood glucose levels throughout the day and night.
Popular CGM brands include Dexcom, Freestyle Libre, and Medtronic.

Fitness trackers with heart rate monitoring - Wearable fitness trackers like Fitbit, Garmin, or Apple Watch can help users track physical activity, sleep quality, and heart rate, all of which are important indicators of overall health.
Insulin Pumps - Many insulin pumps now come equipped with built-in trackers that monitor insulin dosing, carb counting, and blood glucose levels.
Insulin Pumps - Some insulin pumps like the Omnipod System have built-in features that allow users to track their insulin doses, carb ratios, and blood glucose levels.

Fitbit and Garmin Wearables - While not specifically designed for diabetes management, these wearables can track physical activity, sleep patterns, and heart rate, all of which are important for overall health.
Fitness trackers with built-in glucose tracking - Some fitness trackers like Fitbit and Garmin have partnered with companies like Livongo to integrate glucose tracking into their wearable devices.
